 <title>PSH-16-0084  - In the Matter of Personnel Security Hearing</title>
 <link>https://energy.gov/oha/downloads/psh-16-0084-matter-personnel-security-hearing</link>
 <description>&lt;a href=&quot;/oha/downloads/psh-16-0084-matter-personnel-security-hearing&quot; class=&quot;title-link&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;PSH-16-0084  - In the Matter of Personnel Security Hearing&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div  property=&quot;content:encoded&quot; class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;On January 13, 2017, an Administrative Judge (AJ) issued a decision in which he determined that an individual’s access authorization should be restored.  The individual had accumulated medical debts as the result of hospitalization in 2012 and had not repaid them by July 2016.  The Local Security Office (LSO) conducted a Personnel Security Interviews (PSI) of the individual in July 2016 to address concerns about his financial irresponsibility, as demonstrated in part by his failure to carry through on his commitments to address his debts made during a 2013 OPM interview.   At the hearing, the individual testified that he was laid off for much of the two years following the 2013 OPM interview, and his wife was laid off at the same time.  She later filed for disability benefits, retroactive to 2013.  He established that the cause of his indebtedness was his hospitalization followed by periods of unemployment, both of which were beyond his control.    He did not address his debts as he had promised because, once laid off, he had no surplus income with which to pay any debts; moreover, they anticipated resolving those debts by using his wife’s lump-sum payment for retroactive disability, which they had been assured would be issued promptly.  By July 2016, he understood that those payments were not forthcoming in the near future, and arranged to repay all his outstanding debts by refinancing his mortgage.  At the time of the hearing, he had paid all his creditors and had steady work unlikely to be interrupted by future layoffs.  In addition, he and his wife live frugally, carry no current debt, and can meet all their expenses regardless to whether she receives disability benefits. After reviewing the testimony, the AJ determined that the individual had resolved the LSO’s security concerns under Criterion L.  OHA Case No. PSH-16-0084 (William Schwartz, Administrative Judge)&lt;/p&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-download-files field-type-file field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div  class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;media-link-wrapper&quot; href=&quot;https://energy.gov/sites/prod/files/2017/01/f34/PSH-16-0084.pdf&quot;&gt;&lt;img typeof=&quot;foaf:Image&quot; src=&quot;/modules/file/icons/application-pdf.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;filename&quot;&gt;PSH-16-0084.pdf&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;filesize&quot;&gt;(168.56 KB)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
