<item>
 <title>PSH-16-0072 - In the Matter of Personnel Security Hearing</title>
 <link>https://energy.gov/oha/downloads/psh-16-0072-matter-personnel-security-hearing</link>
 <description>&lt;a href=&quot;/oha/downloads/psh-16-0072-matter-personnel-security-hearing&quot; class=&quot;title-link&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;PSH-16-0072 - In the Matter of Personnel Security Hearing&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div  property=&quot;content:encoded&quot; class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;On November 22, 2016, an OHA Administrative Judge issued a decision in which she determined that an individual’s access authorization should be restored.  In reaching this determination, the Administrative Judge found that the individual had resolved the security concerns arising from a diagnosis that the individual suffers from Alcohol Abuse, a mental condition which causes, or may cause, a significant defect in judgment or reliability.  In addition, the Local Security Office (LSO) found that individual had engaged in questionable conduct when he knowingly consumed alcohol even though his May 2015 Simple Assault arrest required abstinence.  Further, the LSO found that the individual’s May 2008 and May 2015 Simple Assault arrests and November 2015 Driving Under the Influence arrest raised security concerns regarding the individual’s trustworthiness and reliability.  The individual’s witnesses testified that the individual is extremely trustworthy and honest.  The individual testified that he was upset about his failing marriage, which ultimately ended in divorce, when he consumed alcohol in November 2015.  It was the first and only time he consumed alcohol while required to maintain abstinence after his May 2015 Simple Assault arrest.  After hearing all the testimony, the DOE psychologist testified that the individual was reformed from his Alcohol Abuse diagnosis.  She was impressed with his support system and that he recognized that his marriage had been toxic for him.  Therefore, the Administrative Judge found that the individual had resolved the Criteria H, J, and L security concerns.  OHA Case No. PSH-16-0072 (Janet R. H. Fishman)&lt;/p&gt;
