<item>
 <title>PSH-16-0071 - In the Matter of Personnel Security Hearing</title>
 <link>https://energy.gov/oha/downloads/psh-16-0071-matter-personnel-security-hearing</link>
 <description>&lt;a href=&quot;/oha/downloads/psh-16-0071-matter-personnel-security-hearing&quot; class=&quot;title-link&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;PSH-16-0071 - In the Matter of Personnel Security Hearing&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div  property=&quot;content:encoded&quot; class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;On November 22, 2016, an Administrative Judge (AJ) issued a decision in which he determined that an individual’s request for access authorization should be granted.  The individual had accumulated unpaid debts and had failed to pay his federal taxes for a number of years between 2004 and 2014.  The Local Security Office (LSO) conducted Personnel Security Interviews (PSIs) of the individual in January and April 2016 to address concerns about his financial irresponsibility, as demonstrated in part by his failure to carry through on his commitments to the LSO to address his debts.  At the hearing, the individual testified that his debts and outstanding tax liability accrued during several years of underemployment, when he took out payday loans and claimed 99 dependents on his tax withholding forms, in order to maximize his take-home pay.  He established that the cause of his indebtedness was his underemployment, which has been alleviated by his current position at a DOE facility.  He demonstrated that he has taken responsibility for his debts by attempting to contact each of his creditors and, where possible, entering into payment arrangements with them, including the IRS.  He also testified that he does not claim 99 dependents now that he has consistent employment, and will not do so in the future.  After reviewing the testimony, the AJ determined that the individual had resolved the LSO’s security concern under Criterion L.  OHA Case No. PSH-16-0071 (William Schwartz)&lt;/p&gt;
